01036           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN73XX) && (((offset >= 1) && (offset <= 3)))) ||
01037           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX) && ((offset <= 3))) ||
01038           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX_PASS1_X) && ((offset <= 3))) ||
01039           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CNF75XX) && ((offset <= 1)))))
01040         cvmx_warn("CVMX_PEMX_SPI_CTL(%lu) is invalid on this chip\n", offset);
01041     return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00011800C0000180ull) + ((offset) & 3) * 0x1000000ull;
01042 }
01043 #else
01044 #define CVMX_PEMX_SPI_CTL(offset) (CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00011800C0000180ull) + ((offset) & 3) * 0x1000000ull)
01045 #endif
01046 #if CVMX_ENABLE_CSR_ADDRESS_CHECKING
01047 static inline uint64_t CVMX_PEMX_SPI_DATA(unsigned long offset)
01048 {
01049     if (!(
01050           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN70XX) && ((offset <= 2))) ||
01051           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN73XX) && (((offset >= 1) && (offset <= 3)))) ||
01052           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX) && ((offset <= 3))) ||
01053           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX_PASS1_X) && ((offset <= 3))) ||
01054           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CNF75XX) && ((offset <= 1)))))
01055         cvmx_warn("CVMX_PEMX_SPI_DATA(%lu) is invalid on this chip\n", offset);
01056     return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00011800C0000188ull) + ((offset) & 3) * 0x1000000ull;
01057 }
01058 #else
01059 #define CVMX_PEMX_SPI_DATA(offset) (CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00011800C0000188ull) + ((offset) & 3) * 0x1000000ull)
01060 #endif
01061 #if CVMX_ENABLE_CSR_ADDRESS_CHECKING
01062 static inline uint64_t CVMX_PEMX_STRAP(unsigned long offset)
01063 {
01064     if (!(
01065           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN70XX) && ((offset <= 2))) ||
01066           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN73XX) && (((offset >= 1) && (offset <= 3)))) ||
01067           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX) && ((offset <= 3))) ||

01072 }
01073 #else
01074 #define CVMX_PEMX_STRAP(offset) (CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00011800C0000408ull) + ((offset) & 3) * 0x1000000ull)
01075 #endif
01076 #if CVMX_ENABLE_CSR_ADDRESS_CHECKING
01077 static inline uint64_t CVMX_PEMX_TLP_CREDITS(unsigned long offset)
01078 {
01079     if (!(
01080           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN61XX) && ((offset <= 1))) ||
01081           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN63XX) && ((offset <= 1))) ||
01082           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN66XX) && ((offset <= 1))) ||
01083           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN68XX) && ((offset <= 1))) ||
01084           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN70XX) && ((offset <= 2))) ||
01085           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN73XX) && (((offset >= 1) && (offset <= 3)))) ||
01086           (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX) && ((offset <= 3))) ||

01514                                                          When set, the PEM is configured to be a Root Complex.

01520                                                          lanes than the specified maximum can be configured for use via
01521                                                          the core's Link Control Register (CFG032) Negotiated Link Width
01522                                                          field.

01528                                                            011 - Rsvd

01530                                                            101 - Gen1 Speed, 1-lane

01546                                                          performed to/from the SerDes. When clear, no lane swapping is performed. */
01547     uint64_t lanes8                       : 1;  /**< This field enables overwriting the value for the maximum number of lanes. The reset value
01548                                                          is captured on cold reset by the pin straps (see PEM()_STRAP[PILANES8]). When set, the
01549                                                          PEM is configured for a maximum of 8 lanes when connected to a QLM. When clear, the PEM
01550                                                          is configured for a maximum of 4 lanes when connected to a QLM. When the PEM is connected
01551                                                          to a DLM, this field is unused, the number of lanes is 2.
01552                                                          This value, along with PEM()_QLM[PEMDLMMUX], is used to set the maximum link width field
01553                                                          in the core's

01556                                                          the core's link control register (CFG032) negotiated link width field. */

01558                                                          cold reset by the pin straps. (See PEM()_STRAP[PIMODE]. The HOSTMD reset value is the
01559                                                          bit-wise AND of the PIMODE straps.  As such, PEMs 0 and 2 are configurable and PEMs 1
01560                                                          and 3 default to 0x1.)  When set, the PEM is configured to be a root complex. When clear,
01561                                                          the PEM is configured to be an end point.

01777                                                          and retry status is received for a configuration read, the read will be
01778                                                          resent. A value of 0 disables retries and treats a CPL Retry as a CPL UR.
01779                                                          To use, it is recommended CFG_RTRY be set value corresponding to 200 ms or less, although
01780                                                          the PCI Express Base Specification allows up to 900 ms for a device to send a successful

01792                                                          active when in RC mode. */

01826     uint64_t pbus                         : 8;  /**< Primary bus number. */
01827     uint64_t reserved_32_33               : 2;
01828     uint64_t cfg_rtry                     : 16; /**< The time x 0x10000 in core clocks to wait for a
01829                                                          CPL to a CFG RD that does not carry a Retry Status.
01830                                                          Until such time that the timeout occurs and Retry
01831                                                          Status is received for a CFG RD, the Read CFG Read
01832                                                          will be resent. A value of 0 disables retries and
01833                                                          treats a CPL Retry as a CPL UR.
01834                                                          When enabled only one CFG RD may be issued until
01835                                                          either successful completion or CPL UR. */

01915     uint64_t fast_lm                      : 1;  /**< When set, forces fast link mode. */

01948 /**
01949  * cvmx_pem#_ctl_status2
01950  *
01951  * This register contains additional general control and status of the PEM.
01952  *
01953  */
01954 union cvmx_pemx_ctl_status2 {
01955     uint64_t u64;
01956     struct cvmx_pemx_ctl_status2_s {
01957 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01958     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
01959     uint64_t no_fwd_prg                   : 16; /**< The time * 0x10000 in core clocks to wait for the TLP FIFOs to be able to unload an entry.
01960                                                          If there is no forward progress, such that the timeout occurs, credits are returned to the
01961                                                          SLI and an interrupt (if enabled) is asserted. Any more TLPs received are dropped on the
01962                                                          floor and the credits associated with those TLPs are returned as well. Note that 0xFFFF is
01963                                                          a reserved value that will put the PEM in the 'forward progress stopped' state
01964                                                          immediately. This state holds until a MAC reset is received. */
01965 #else
01966     uint64_t no_fwd_prg                   : 16;
01967     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
01968 #endif
01969     } s;

01974 };

03379 /**
03380  * cvmx_pem#_flr_pf0_vf_stopreq
03381  *
03382  * Hardware automatically sets the STOPREQ bit for the VF when it enters a
03383  * Function Level Reset (FLR).  Software is responsible for clearing the STOPREQ
03384  * bit but must not do so prior to hardware taking down the FLR, which could be
03385  * as long as 100ms.  It may be appropriate for software to wait longer before clearing
03386  * STOPREQ, software may need to drain deep DPI queues for example.
03387  * Whenever PEM receives a request mastered by CNXXXX over S2M (i.e. P or NP),
03388  * when STOPREQ is set for the function, PEM will discard the outgoing request
03389  * before sending it to the PCIe core.  If a NP, PEM will schedule an immediate
03390  * SWI_RSP_ERROR completion for the request - no timeout is required.
03391  *
03392  * STOPREQ mimics the behavior of PCIEEPVF()_CFG001[ME] for outbound requests that will
03393  * master the PCIe bus (P and NP).
03394  *
03395  * Note that STOPREQ will have no effect on completions returned by CNXXXX over the S2M,
03396  * nor on M2S traffic.
03397  */
03398 union cvmx_pemx_flr_pf0_vf_stopreq {
03399     uint64_t u64;
03400     struct cvmx_pemx_flr_pf0_vf_stopreq_s {
03401 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03402     uint64_t vf_stopreq                   : 64; /**< STOPREQ for the 64 VFs in PF0. */
03403 #else
03404     uint64_t vf_stopreq                   : 64;
03405 #endif
03406     } s;
03407     struct cvmx_pemx_flr_pf0_vf_stopreq_s cn73xx;
03408     struct cvmx_pemx_flr_pf0_vf_stopreq_s cn78xx;
03409     struct cvmx_pemx_flr_pf0_vf_stopreq_s cnf75xx;
03410 };
03411 typedef union cvmx_pemx_flr_pf0_vf_stopreq cvmx_pemx_flr_pf0_vf_stopreq_t;
03412 
03413 /**
03414  * cvmx_pem#_flr_pf_stopreq
03415  *
03416  * Hardware automatically sets the STOPREQ bit for the PF when it enters a
03417  * Function Level Reset (FLR).  Software is responsible for clearing the STOPREQ
03418  * bit but must not do so prior to hardware taking down the FLR, which could be
03419  * as long as 100ms.  It may be appropriate for software to wait longer before clearing
03420  * STOPREQ, software may need to drain deep DPI queues for example.
03421  * Whenever PEM receives a PF or child VF request mastered by CNXXXX over S2M (i.e. P or NP),
03422  * when STOPREQ is set for the function, PEM will discard the outgoing request
03423  * before sending it to the PCIe core.  If a NP, PEM will schedule an immediate
03424  * SWI_RSP_ERROR completion for the request - no timeout is required.
03425  *
03426  * STOPREQ mimics the behavior of PCIEEP()_CFG001[ME] for outbound requests that will
03427  * master the PCIe bus (P and NP).
03428  *
03429  * Note that STOPREQ will have no effect on completions returned by CNXXXX over the S2M,
03430  * nor on M2S traffic.
03431  *
03432  * Note that when a PF()_STOPREQ is set, none of the associated
03433  * PEM()_FLR_PF()_VF_STOPREQ[VF_STOPREQ]
03434  * will be set.
03435  */
03436 union cvmx_pemx_flr_pf_stopreq {
03437     uint64_t u64;
03438     struct cvmx_pemx_flr_pf_stopreq_s {
03439 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03440     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
03441     uint64_t pf0_stopreq                  : 1;  /**< PF0 STOPREQ bit. */
03442 #else
03443     uint64_t pf0_stopreq                  : 1;
03444     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
03445 #endif
03446     } s;
03447     struct cvmx_pemx_flr_pf_stopreq_s     cn73xx;
03448     struct cvmx_pemx_flr_pf_stopreq_s     cn78xx;
03449     struct cvmx_pemx_flr_pf_stopreq_s     cnf75xx;
03450 };
03451 typedef union cvmx_pemx_flr_pf_stopreq cvmx_pemx_flr_pf_stopreq_t;

03453 /**
03454  * cvmx_pem#_flr_stopreq_ctl
03455  */
03456 union cvmx_pemx_flr_stopreq_ctl {
03457     uint64_t u64;
03458     struct cvmx_pemx_flr_stopreq_ctl_s {
03459 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03460     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
03461     uint64_t stopreqclr                   : 1;  /**< When [STOPREQCLR] is clear, only software (and reset) can clear
03462                                                          PEM(0)_FLR_PF_STOPREQ[STOPREQ] and PEM(0)_FLR_PF0_VF_STOPREQ[STOPREQ].
03463                                                          When STOPREQCLR is set, PEM hardware
03464                                                          also clears the STOPREQ bit when PEM completes an FLR to the PCIe core. In the
03465                                                          case of a VF, only one STOPREQ bit gets cleared upon each FLR ack when
03466                                                          STOPREQCLR mode bit is set. The srst will assert upon a PF
03467                                                          FLR, and srst could be used to reset all STOPREQ bits regardless of
03468                                                          STOPREQCLR. Otherwise (e.g. [ProductLine]), where a PF FLR does not
03469                                                          assert srst. */
03470 #else
03471     uint64_t stopreqclr                   : 1;
03472     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
03473 #endif
03474     } s;

03732                                                          (radm_pm_pme) */

04174 /**
04175  * cvmx_pem#_spi_ctl
04176  *
04177  * PEM#_SPI_CTL register.
04178  *
04179  */
04180 union cvmx_pemx_spi_ctl {
04181     uint64_t u64;
04182     struct cvmx_pemx_spi_ctl_s {
04183 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04184     uint64_t reserved_14_63               : 50;
04185     uint64_t start_busy                   : 1;  /**< Start/Busy status. When written with a one, indicates to the controller to
04186                                                          start a SPI transaction. The controller clears [START_BUSY] when the
04187                                                          write/read operation has completed. If the operation was a read, the
04188                                                          contents of PEM()_SPI_DATA are valid once hardware clears this bit. */
04189     uint64_t tvalid                       : 1;  /**< Reads 1 if at least one valid entry was read (preamble was valid) from EEPROM
04190                                                          and written to corresponding PEM()_SPI_DATA. Write to clear status. */
04191     uint64_t cmd                          : 3;  /**< SPI commands. The commands are the following:
04192                                                          0x0 = Reserved.
04193                                                          0x1 = WRSR: write status register. A single-byte write of
04194                                                                corresponding PEM()_SPI_DATA[DATA<7:0>] to the register.
04195                                                          0x2 = WRITE: an eight-byte page-mode write of the 64-bits of corresponding
04196                                                                PEM()_SPI_DATA to the memory array.
04197                                                          0x3 = READ: an eight-byte page-mode read access from the memory array
04198                                                                with result in the 64-bits of corresponding PEM()_SPI_DATA.
04199                                                          0x4 = WRDI: clear the write-enable latch (i.e. write protect the device).
04200                                                          0x5 = RDSR: Read status register. A single-byte read access from
04201                                                                the register with result in corresponding PEM()_SPI_DATA[DATA<7:0>].
04202                                                          0x6 = WREN: set the write-enable latch (i.e. allow writes to occur).
04203                                                          0x7 = Reserved. */
04204     uint64_t adr                          : 9;  /**< EEPROM read/write address. the byte address offset for the serial EEPROM access.
04205                                                          Since accesses are eight-byte aligned entries, <2:0> must be zero. */
04206 #else
04207     uint64_t adr                          : 9;
04208     uint64_t cmd                          : 3;
04209     uint64_t tvalid                       : 1;
04210     uint64_t start_busy                   : 1;
04211     uint64_t reserved_14_63               : 50;
04212 #endif
04213     } s;
04214     struct cvmx_pemx_spi_ctl_s            cn70xx;
04215     struct cvmx_pemx_spi_ctl_s            cn70xxp1;

04223 /**
04224  * cvmx_pem#_spi_data
04225  *
04226  * This register contains the most recently read or written SPI data and is unpredictable upon
04227  * power-up. Is valid after a PEM()_SPI_CTL[CMD]=READ/RDSR when hardware clears
04228  * PEM()_SPI_CTL[START_BUSY]. Is written after a PEM()_SPI_CTL[CMD]=WRITE/WRSR
04229  * when hardware clears PEM()_SPI_CTL[START_BUSY].
04230  */
04231 union cvmx_pemx_spi_data {
04232     uint64_t u64;
04233     struct cvmx_pemx_spi_data_s {
04234 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04235     uint64_t preamble                     : 16; /**< EEPROM PREAMBLE read or write data:
04236                                                             valid entry  = 0x9DA1
04237                                                             end-of-table = 0x6A5D
04238                                                             null         = 0xFFFF
04239                                                          Unpredictable after a PEM()_SPI_CTL[CMD]=RDSR. */
04240     uint64_t reserved_45_47               : 3;
04241     uint64_t cs2                          : 1;  /**< EEPROM CS2 bit. See PEM()_CFG_WR[ADDR<31>]. The [CS2] from
04242                                                          a valid EEPROM entry selects the type of write. When clear, an ordinary
04243                                                          configuration write. When set, a configuration mask write.
04244                                                          Unpredictable after a PEM()_SPI_CTL[CMD]=RDSR. */
04245     uint64_t adr                          : 12; /**< EEPROM configuration register address. See PEM()_CFG_WR[ADDR<11:0>].
04246                                                          The [ADR] from a valid EEPROM entry selects which configuration register
04247                                                          will be written. Note that PEM()_CFG_WR[ADDR<30:12>] of the effective
04248                                                          write are all zeroes.
04249                                                          Unpredictable after a PEM()_SPI_CTL[CMD]=RDSR. */
04250     uint64_t data                         : 32; /**< EEPROM configuration register data. See PEM()_CFG_WR[DATA].
04251                                                          HW writes the [DATA] from a valid EEPROM entry to the selected register.
04252                                                          [DATA<31:8>] are unpredictable after a PEM()_SPI_CTL[CMD]=RDSR. */
04253 #else
04254     uint64_t data                         : 32;
04255     uint64_t adr                          : 12;
04256     uint64_t cs2                          : 1;
04257     uint64_t reserved_45_47               : 3;
04258     uint64_t preamble                     : 16;
04259 #endif
04260     } s;
04261     struct cvmx_pemx_spi_data_s           cn70xx;
04262     struct cvmx_pemx_spi_data_s           cn70xxp1;

04385 /**
04386  * cvmx_pem#_tlp_credits
04387  *
04388  * This register specifies the number of credits for use in moving TLPs. When this register is
04389  * written, the credit values are reset to the register value. A write to this register should
04390  * take place before traffic flow starts.
04391  */
04392 union cvmx_pemx_tlp_credits {
04393     uint64_t u64;
04394     struct cvmx_pemx_tlp_credits_s {
04395 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04396     uint64_t reserved_56_63               : 8;
04397     uint64_t peai_ppf                     : 8;  /**< TLP credits for Completion TLPs in the Peer.
04398                                                          The value in this register should not be changed.
04399                                                          Values other than 0x80 can lead to unpredictable
04400                                                          behavior */
04401     uint64_t pem_cpl                      : 8;  /**< TLP 16B credits for completion TLPs in the peer. Legal values are 0x12 to 0x40. */
04402     uint64_t pem_np                       : 8;  /**< TLP 16B credits for nonposted TLPs in the peer. Legal values are 0x4 to 0x8. */
04403     uint64_t pem_p                        : 8;  /**< TLP 16B credits for posted TLPs in the peer. Legal values are 0x12 to 0x40. */
04404     uint64_t sli_cpl                      : 8;  /**< TLP 8B credits for completion TLPs in the SLI. Legal values are 0x24 to
04405                                                          0xFF. Pairs of PEMs share a single SLI interface. When both PEM(0) and PEM(1)
04406                                                          are configured, the sum of both PEMs' SLI_CPL fields must not exceed 0x100. The
04407                                                          reset value for this register assumes the minimum (e.g. 2-lane)
04408                                                          configuration. This ensures the total allocated credits does not
04409                                                          oversubscribe the SLI.
04410                                                          For configurations other than two 2-lane PEMs connected to a single SLI port,
04411                                                          software may safely reprogram this register (i.e. increase the value) to achieve
04412                                                          optimal performance.  See the following table of example configurations of PEM
04413                                                          pairs for recommended credit values.
04414                                                          <pre>
04415                                                             Configuration  PEM  Lanes  Typical [SLI_CPL]
04416                                                             --------------------------------------------
04417                                                             1 4-ln PEM     n    4             0xFF
04418                                                             2 2-ln PEM,   n     2             0x80
04419                                                             2 2-ln PEM,   n+1   2             0x80
04420                                                             1 2-ln PEM    n     2             0xFF
04421                                                          </pre> */
